    {{!-- FACILITATION MODAL............... --}}
    <div class="modal fade" id="facilitationNoteModal" tabindex="-1">
        <div class="modal-dialog modal-dialog-centered modal-lg">
            <div class="modal-content">

                <div class="modal-header">
                    <h2 class="modal-title text-primary">Facilitation Notes</h2>
                    <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal"></button>
                </div>

                <div class="modal-body">

                    <h4>Logistics</h4>

                    <ul>
                        <li>Each session lasts between 40 to 50 minutes, depending upon the number of
                            students
                            and
                            their learning ability.</li>

                        <li>The main resources for the program are 30 phonics reading charts that must be
                            put up
                            on
                            walls during sessions. If possible, keep the charts up on the walls for students
                            to
                            read
                            them during their free time. Make one or two students responsible for the safety
                            of
                            the
                            charts.</li>

                        <li>Intersperse phonics reading charts activities with reading/speaking activities.
                            We
                            have
                            a set of matching cards, speaking activities and books that can be used to make
                            classes
                            engaging (See Annexure 1-12).</li>

                        <li>The sessions mentioned are only for an estimate or a plan. There is a lot of
                            overlaps
                            between charts and number of sessions listed. A single session could be used for
                            teaching multiple charts.</li>

                        <li>If a class doesn’t catch up in a particular objective, feel free to roll back,
                            slow
                            down
                            and repeat.</li>

                        <li>Comprehension of sentences is as important as being able to read. Ensure that
                            every
                            sentence is not just read, but understood.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>Dealing with Struggling Students</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            Remember, anyone can teach a student who already has a good base in reading. A
                            good
                            facilitator/teacher is one who can help struggling students catch up and learn
                            to
                            read.
                            This is the main objective of a FiRST PiCk Phonics facilitator.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            If a student or two are struggling, seek help from other students to bring them
                            up
                            to
                            the
                            level during their free time. Most student like the additional responsibility
                            and
                            want
                            to
                            teach others.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            If there are two of you facilitating a class, split the class into two groups.
                            Paying
                            attention
                            to individual students helps them learn faster.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            It is likely that a few students do not catch up despite personal attention.
                            Discuss
                            these
                            situations with the class teacher, who can then help you decide the best course
                            of
                            action.
                            This is especially relevant for students with intellectual or reading
                            disabilities
                            because we
                            are not equipped to deal with these issues.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Appreciate effort made by students. Use appreciation words like “very good”
                            often
                            and
                            encourage students to clap for each other. If a struggling student makes
                            progress,
                            highlight it to the entire class and applaud the achievement.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>Dealing with Indiscipline</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            Two key elements to facilitate learning in young students is engagement and lack
                            of
                            fear.
                            Facilitators must not use verbal or physical violence of any kind. If a class is
                            unruly
                            or
                            inattentive, it is the facilitator’s task to get their attention by changing the
                            activity
                            being
                            done, or by adding elements of engagement in their teaching. Only in exceptional
                            cases
                            should students be asked to leave the class, after consulting with the class
                            teacher
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>Fostering Cooperation Versus Competition </h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            Unlike school education, where competition among students is the motivator, the
                            FiRST
                            PiCk Phonics program considers cooperation as its cornerstone. Facilitators must
                            never
                            let
                            any student feel they are better or worse than others.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            A student who comprehends a certain concept faster than others should be
                            encouraged
                            to teach others. Applaud cooperation and empathy towards fellow classmates more
                            than
                            individual achievements.
                        </li>
                        <li>Individual competitions should never be used to encourage learning. Use team
                            competitions, which foster cooperation among team members while competing with
                            another team.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>Progress Tracking and Annual Performance </h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Before implementing the Phonics Program, we conduct a Reading Assessment
                            (Annexure
                            12). This gives us an idea of the current reading levels of students. The same
                            Assessment
                            is conducted at the end of the year and the progress of the students is
                            recorded.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Most primary school children in rural India will never have the opportunity to
                            come
                            on
                            stage and perform. FiRST PiCk, being primarily a theatre and poetry club,
                            provides
                            such
                            an
                            opportunity to students, combining theatre with English reading and speaking.
                            The
                            FiRST
                            PiCk Phonics Program in every school must culminate in an annual function that
                            includes
                            skits, plays, poems, dances and reading activities, all in English.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

